## Bash Execution Rules

Always run each command as a separate Bash call.

Never chain commands using `&&`, `||`, `;`, or `|` in a single Bash call.

Shell operators break the tool's permission matching entirely — compound commands are unmatchable by design and always trigger an unavoidable approval prompt regardless of permission settings.

Bad:

```
cd "/Users/mtm/Documents/Obsidian Vault" && git add "file.md" && git commit -m "message"
```

Good:

```
cd "/Users/mtm/Documents/Obsidian Vault"
```

```
git add "file.md"
```

```
git commit -m "message"
```

Or, if the working directory is already correct, skip the `cd` entirely and issue each remaining command in its own call.

This applies to all commands, not just git.
